Hiding Login/Password as Environment Variables

  • cd ~
  • nano .bash_profile
  • export USER="jdoe"
  • export PASS="1234"
  • ctrl-x, y
  • source .bash_profile

CRONTAB

  • Flags(-l:list, -r:remove, -e:edit)
  • Use shell scripts(<scriptname.sh>
  • Include "shebang" (#!bin/bash) as first line of shell script
  • Export environment variables in shell script
  • Use absolute path(/home/user/path/to/*)
  • Use "." in place of "source" command for crontab
  • Give file 744 permission(chmod 744 .)
  • Use "MAILTO='foo@bar.net'" as first line in crontab to receive notification of every cronjob
  • Cron logs to /var/log/syslog
  • For cron specific logs(grep CRON /var/log/syslog)

Exec as root

  • sudo docker exec -u 0 -it <mycontainer> <bash(ubuntu) or sh(alpine)>

sudo docker-compose up - starts all containers sudo docker-compose up -d - starts named container

Stop all running containers

  • sudo docker stop $(sudo docker ps -a -q)
  • sudo docker-compose down

Create a volume

  • sudo docker volume create <name>

Named Volume

  • sudo docker run -dp 3000:3000 -v todo-db:/etc/todos <tag>

Bind Mount

  • sudo docker run -dp 3000:3000 \ -w /app -v $PWD:/app \ node:10-alpine \ sh -c "yarn install && yarn run dev"

Create Network

  • sudo docker network create todo-app

Connecting to MYSQL

  • sudo docker run -dp 3000:3000 \ -w /app -v $PWD:/app \ --network todo-app \ -e MYSQL_HOST=mysql \ -e MYSQL_USER=root \ -e MYSQL_PASSWORD=secret \ -e MYSQL_DB=todos \ node:10-alpine \ sh -c "yarn install && yarn run dev"

Enter MYSQL

  • sudo docker exec -ti mysql -p todos

Getting Started with Jenkins

SchoolofDevops-learn-jenkins

  • install pipeline plugin
  • fork and clone source code
  • cd to directory
  • create Jenkinsfile with $ nano Jenkinsfile
  • git add Jenkinsfile, commit and push origin master
  • create new item as pipeline, include repo link

BUILDOZER¶

Build a Mobile App- @realpython

Buildozer Dependencies

Setup

  • pip3 install buildozer
  • Then, create a new folder and navigate to it in your terminal. Once you’re there, you’ll need to run the following command:
  • buildozer init

  • This will create a buildozer.spec file that you’ll use to configure your build. For this example, you can edit the first few lines of the spec file as follows: [app]

  • (str) Title of your application title = KvCalc

  • (str) Package name package.name = kvcalc

  • (str) Package domain (needed for android/ios packaging) package.domain = org.kvcalc

  • At this point, you’re almost ready to build your application, but first, you’ll want to install the dependencies for buildozer. Once those are installed, copy your calculator application into your new folder and rename it to main.py. This is required by buildozer. If you don’t have the file named correctly, then the build will fail.

  • buildozer -v android debug

FLASK¶

Basic Setup

  • Create python virtual environment (python3 -m venv <env_name>)
  • Activate virtual environment (source <env_name>/bin/activate)
  • Create a basic python script without html 
from flask import Flask
app = Flask(__name__)
@app.route('/')
def hello():
    return "Hello World!"
if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run()
  • Create a templates folder for .html files (mkdir templates)
  • Create a basic python script with html
from flask import Flask, render_template
app = Flask(__name__)
@app.route('/')
def home():
    return render_template('<name\>.html')
if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run()

Debug Mode

if __name__ == '__main__':
app.run(debug=True)

Basic UnitTest

import <project>
import unittest


class MyTestCase(unittest.TestCase):

def setUp(self):
    <project>.app.testing = True
    self.app = <project>.app.test_client()

def test_home(self):
    response = self.app.get('/')
    # Make your assertions
    self.assertEqual(response.status_code, 200)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    unittest.main()

DEPLOYING FLASK APP TO LINUX SERVER¶

Setup ssh in Remote Server

  • # ssh root@<ip_address>
  • # apt update && apt upgrade
  • # hostnamectl set-hostname <name>
  • # nano /etc/hosts (add ip and hostname)

/etc/hosts

127.0.0.1       localhost
<ip_address\>  <hostname\>
 The following lines are desirable for IPv6 capable hosts
::1     localhost ip6-localhost ip6-loopback
ff02::1 ip6-allnodes
ff02::2 ip6-allrouters
  • # adduser <username>
  • # adduser <username> sudo
  • # ssh <username>@
  • \$ mkdir ~/.ssh

Local Machine

  • \$ ssh-keygen -b 4096
  • \$ scp ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub <username>@<ip_address>:~/.ssh/authorized_keys

Remote Server

  • \$ sudo chmod 700 ~/.ssh/
  • \$ sudo chmod 600 ~/.ssh/*

Disable Root on Remote Server

  • \$ sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config (PasswordAuthentication=no, PermitRootLogin=no)
  • \$ sudo systemctl restart sshd

Firewall for Remote Server

  • \$ sudo apt install ufw
  • \$ sudo ufw default allow outgoing
  • \$ sudo ufw default deny incoming
  • \$ sudo ufw allow ssh
  • \$ sudo ufw allow 5000
  • \$ sudo ufw enable
  • \$ sudo ufw status

After Installing Nginx

  • \$ sudo ufw allow http/tcp
  • \$ sudo ufw delete allow 5000

Create requirements.txt on Local Machine

  • \$ pip3 freeze > requirements.txt
  • \$ scp -r ~/<project_folder> <username>@<ip_address>:~/

Configure App on Remote Server

  • \$ sudo apt install python3-pip
  • \$ sudo apt install python3-venv
  • \$ python3 -m venv <<project_folder>/<environment_name>>
  • \$ cd <project_folder>
  • \$ source <environment_name>/bin/activate
  • \$ pip install -r requirements.txt

Optional

To create a json file for environment variables

  • \$ sudo touch /etc/confg.json
  • \$ sudo nano config.py Update to access environment variables from config.json with .get() method

Run Flask with Default server

  • \$ export FLASK_APP=<project_name>.py
  • \$ flask run --host=0.0.0.0

Install Nginx and Gunicorn on Remote Server

  • \$ sudo apt install nginx
  • \$ pip install gunicorn
  • \$ sudo rm /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default
  • \$ sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/<project_name>

Nginx configuration <project_name>

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name <ip_address>;
    location /static {
         alias /home/<username>/<project_folder>/static;
    }
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8000;
        include /etc/nginx/proxy_params;
        proxy_redirect off;
    }

}

Update Firewall

  • \$ sudo ufw allow http/tcp
  • \$ sudo ufw delete allow 5000

Restart Nginx

  • \$ sudo systemctl restart nginx

Install Supervisor

  • \$ sudo apt install supervisor
  • \$ sudo nano /etc/supervisor/conf.d/<project_name>.conf

<project_name>.conf

[program:jupyter_page]
directory=/home/jmrobinson/jupyterpage
command=/home/jmrobinson/jupyterpage/jupyter_env/bin/gunicorn -w 3 jupyter_page>
user=jmrobinson
autostart=true
autorestart=true
stopasgroup=true
killasgroup=true
stderr_logfile=/var/log/jupyterpage/jupyterpage.err.log
stdout_logfile=/var/log/jupyterpage/jupyterpage.out.log

Create Log Files

  • \$ sudo touch /var/log/<project_name>/<project_name>.err.log
  • \$ sudo touch /var/log/<project_name>/<project_name>.out.log
  • \$ sudo supervisorctl reload

Encrypt with LetsEncrypt/Certbot

  • \$ sudo apt update
  • \$ sudo apt install software-properties-common
  • \$ sudo add-apt-repository universe
  • \$ sudo add-apt-repository ppa:certbot/certbot
  • \$ sudo apt update
  • \$ sudo apt install python-certbot-nginx The nginx config file may be updated to show domain instead of ip
  • \$ sudo certbot --nginx

Allow Https Traffic Through Firewall

  • \$ sudo ufw allow https

SQLALCHEMY¶

Basic Template

from sqlalchemy import create_engine, Column, String
from sqlalchemy.ext.declarative import declarative_base
from sqlalchemy.orm import sessionmaker, relationship

Base = declarative_base()
class Posts(Base):

    __tablename__ = "base"

    timing = Column(String(120), unique=False, nullable=False,   primary_key=True)
    title_text = Column(String(120), unique=False, nullable=False)
    price = Column(String(120), unique=False, nullable=False)
    link = Column(String(120), unique=False, nullable=False)

engine = create_engine('sqlite:///search_results.db')  #echo=True for output to console
                             # ^^^ or ////home/user/path/to/folder
Base.metadata.create_all(bind=engine)            
Session = sessionmaker(bind=engine)
session = Session()

session.add(post)
session.commit()
session.close()

Catch IntegrityError

   from sqlalchemy import exc

   try:
       pass
   except exc.IntegrityError as e:
       session.rollback()
